    </div>
    <h1>Review Gating</h1>
    <p class="description">Screening customer satisfaction before requesting a public review — directing happy customers to Google while routing unhappy ones to private forms. <strong>Explicitly prohibited by Google and the FTC.</strong> About 23% of businesses still practice it.</p>
    <div class="post-meta">
      <div class="meta-author">
        <div class="meta-avatar">AVR</div>
        <div class="meta-author-info">
          <span class="meta-author-name"><a href="/authors/akshay-vr/">Akshay VR</a></span>
          <span class="meta-author-role">Marketing Head · theStacc</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Published</span><span class="meta-value">Jul 2026</span></div>
      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Read</span><span class="meta-value">6 min</span></div>
      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Status</span><span class="meta-value">Google Policy Violation</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Review gating</strong> is the practice of screening customer satisfaction before asking for a public review. Businesses send a satisfaction question first — then direct positive respondents to Google or Yelp while routing negative respondents to a private complaint form. Google explicitly prohibits this, stating businesses cannot "discourage or prohibit negative reviews, or selectively solicit positive reviews."</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Google policy</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Explicit violation</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Online Reputation</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Business usage</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~23% (BrightLocal 2024)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">FTC risk</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Six-figure fines</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Review gating feels like a reasonable solution to a real problem — you want more positive reviews and fewer negative ones showing publicly. The issue is that it's deceptive by definition, and both Google and the FTC treat it that way. The alternative isn't to accept every bad review silently; it's to build a review system good enough that a handful of negative reviews don't define your profile.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is review gating?</h2>
        <p>Review gating works through a two-step funnel. First, a business sends a satisfaction survey or asks a simple "how was your experience?" question. Based on the answer, customers are routed differently:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Satisfied customers (4–5 stars):</strong> directed to Google, Yelp, or Facebook with a review request</li>
          <li><strong>Dissatisfied customers (1–3 stars):</strong> directed to a private feedback form that the business sees internally but which never appears publicly</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The result is a public review profile that shows only positive sentiment — an artificial signal that misrepresents the actual distribution of customer experience.</p>
        <p>Google's review policy states explicitly: "Don't discourage or prohibit negative reviews or selectively solicit positive reviews from customers." The FTC, under its endorsement guidelines, considers review gating a form of deceptive advertising because it presents a biased sample as representative consumer opinion.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">The perfect-score problem</div>
          <p>Research consistently shows that star ratings between <strong>4.2–4.8 convert better than a perfect 5.0</strong>. A perfect score raises consumer suspicion. A nearly-perfect score with a handful of critical reviews — including professional business responses — builds more credibility than a flawless profile.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why review gating matters — the risks</h2>
        <p>Review gating creates short-term profile improvement and long-term structural risk. Four reasons it matters beyond the obvious policy violation.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Google can remove all gated reviews.</strong> When Google detects unnatural review patterns — influxes of 5-star reviews with no variation — it can remove reviews in bulk. A dental practice that accumulated 80 five-star reviews through gating had 60 removed after a competitor report, dropping from a 5.0 to a 4.6 overnight.</li>
          <li><strong>GBP suspension risk.</strong> Repeated review policy violations can trigger Google Business Profile suspension — removing your entire local presence from Maps and local search results.</li>
          <li><strong>FTC enforcement reaches six figures.</strong> The FTC has issued significant fines for review manipulation. While enforcement typically targets companies with systematic programs, the precedent is clear: review gating is considered deceptive advertising.</li>
          <li><strong>Filtered reviews appear inauthentic.</strong> Sophisticated consumers identify all-positive profiles as suspicious. A 5.0 rating with 200 reviews and no negative feedback looks manipulated compared to a 4.7 with 200 reviews that includes some critical feedback and business responses.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How review gating works technically — and how Google detects it</h2>
        <p>The typical review gating flow:</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># The gating funnel</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Step 1:</span> Send customer satisfaction rating request (e.g., "How was your visit? 1-5 stars")<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-label">If rating = 4-5:</span> <span class="uf-new">→ Direct to Google / Yelp review form</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">If rating = 1-3:</span> <span class="uf-old">→ Route to private complaint form (internal only)</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># How Google detects this pattern</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Signal:</span> Unusual volume of 5-star reviews · No negative reviews · Sudden influx<br>
          <span class="uf-label">Trigger:</span> Algorithm flag OR competitor report → Manual investigation → Bulk removal
        </div>

        <h3>How Google detects review gating</h3>
        <p>Google's algorithm identifies several unnatural patterns:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Sudden influx of reviews within a short timeframe</li>
          <li>Review profiles with 98%+ positive ratings across hundreds of reviews</li>
          <li>Reviews that cluster in time (e.g., 20 reviews in one week, then nothing for months)</li>
          <li>Similar language patterns across multiple reviews suggesting a templated flow</li>
          <li>Competitor or consumer reports triggering manual investigation</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Review gating vs permitted practices — what's the line?</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Practice</th><th>Permitted?</th><th>Reason</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Asking all customers for reviews</strong></td>
                <td class="cell-yes">Yes</td>
                <td>Google explicitly encourages this</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Asking only satisfied customers for reviews</strong></td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td>Selective solicitation = review gating</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Sending a satisfaction survey before asking</strong></td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td>If routing differs by score, it's gating</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Providing a direct review link</strong></td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td><td>Reducing friction is fine</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Incentivizing reviews</strong></td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td>Violates Google and FTC guidelines</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Responding to negative reviews publicly</strong></td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td><td>Encouraged — shows engagement</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Reporting fake negative reviews</strong></td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td><td>Legitimate platform recourse</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Review gating consequences — real cases</h2>
        <p>Two examples showing how review gating plays out when discovered.</p>

        <h3>1. Dental practice: 60 reviews removed overnight</h3>
        <p>A dental practice used a gating tool to accumulate 80 five-star reviews over six months. A competing practice filed a report with Google citing the suspicious review pattern. Google investigated, identified the gating flow, and removed 60 of the 80 reviews in a bulk action. The practice's rating dropped from 5.0 to 4.6 — a visible change that required months of legitimate review generation to recover from.</p>

        <h3>2. Plumbing company: abandoned gating, built trust</h3>
        <p>A plumbing company stopped gating after learning of the policy risk, switched to asking all customers equally, and accepted that their rating would include some negative feedback. They implemented a 24-hour negative review response policy. Their current profile: 4.7 stars with a mix of ratings and detailed business responses. Customer conversion from their GBP profile improved compared to the period when they had a perfect-looking but sparse profile.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Review gating vs review generation — the better alternative</h2>
        <p>The goal behind review gating is legitimate — more positive reviews, fewer damaging ones publicly visible. The approach is the problem. Review generation solves the same goal without the risk.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="cons-card" style="border-color: #fca5a5; background: #fff5f5;">
            <h4 style="color: #b91c1c;">Review gating (prohibited)</h4>
            <ul style="color: var(--text-1);">
              <li>Screen customers by satisfaction first</li>
              <li>Send review link only to happy customers</li>
              <li>Route unhappy customers to private form</li>
              <li>Creates artificially positive profile</li>
              <li>Google policy violation + FTC risk</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Review generation (permitted)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Ask all customers equally for reviews</li>
              <li>Optimize timing (within 24 hours of service)</li>
              <li>Reduce friction with direct platform links</li>
              <li>Respond to all reviews within 24 hours</li>
              <li>Use negative reviews to identify service gaps</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 compliant review practices to use instead</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Ask all customers equally.</strong> Send review requests to every customer after every transaction — not just the ones who rated you highly in a post-service survey.</li>
          <li><strong>Optimize your timing.</strong> Ask for reviews within 24 hours of a positive experience. The moment of peak satisfaction is when customers are most likely to follow through.</li>
          <li><strong>Remove friction.</strong> Include a direct link to your Google review form. Every extra click a customer has to make reduces completion rate by roughly 20%.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond to negative reviews professionally and quickly.</strong> A well-crafted response that acknowledges the issue and offers resolution impresses future customers who read it. Silence on negative reviews looks worse than the review itself.</li>
          <li><strong>Use negative feedback internally.</strong> Route negative survey responses to your operations or customer service team for follow-up — not to suppress the review, but to fix the underlying issue.</li>
          <li><strong>Build review velocity over perfection.</strong> A steady flow of 10–15 reviews per month at 4.5 stars builds more trust than sporadic bursts of perfect reviews. Velocity signals an active, healthy business.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">If you're currently using a gating tool</div>
          <p>Many reputation management platforms include gating features by default — often marketed as "pre-screening" or "feedback routing." Check your current review software settings. If you're sending a satisfaction question before the review request and routing differently based on the answer, you're gating. Disable it and switch to equal-ask flows immediately to reduce your risk.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common review gating mistakes and misconceptions</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Thinking pre-screening is different from gating</strong> — if the question determines who gets a review request, it's gating regardless of how the tool markets it</li>
          <li><strong>Assuming Google won't find out</strong> — algorithm detection combined with competitor reports makes gating a detectable pattern, not a safe one</li>
          <li><strong>Believing a perfect 5.0 is the goal</strong> — consumer research consistently shows 4.2–4.8 outperforms 5.0 in conversion; aim for a great average, not a perfect one</li>
          <li><strong>Treating negative reviews as pure damage</strong> — a professional response to a negative review can be more persuasive to potential customers than the absence of negative reviews</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the FTC</strong> — while Google enforcement is more immediate, the FTC's endorsement guidelines cover review manipulation and have resulted in six-figure fines for companies with systematic gating programs</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is review gating illegal?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Review gating violates Google's review policies and FTC guidelines on deceptive advertising. While legality varies by jurisdiction, the FTC actively enforces against it with fines reaching six figures. Google can remove gated reviews and penalize your Google Business Profile listing.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can I ask for reviews at all?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Google explicitly encourages businesses to ask for reviews. The key rule: ask all customers equally without filtering by satisfaction level. Do not incentivize reviews or use a pre-screening question to decide who gets the review request.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What if I get a fake negative review?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Report it through your Google Business Profile dashboard. Google removes reviews that violate their policies. For legitimate negative reviews, a professional public response that acknowledges the issue and offers resolution often impresses potential customers more than a blank review record.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Do ratings between 4.2–4.8 really convert better than 5.0?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes, according to multiple consumer research studies including work by Spiegel Research Center. Ratings between 4.2–4.8 are perceived as more authentic than a perfect 5.0. A perfect score raises suspicion; a nearly-perfect score with some critical reviews builds credibility.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How does Google detect review gating?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Google's algorithm identifies unnatural patterns — sudden influxes of 5-star reviews, profiles with 98%+ positive ratings, reviews clustered in time, or similar language across multiple reviews. User and competitor reports also trigger manual investigations.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

